==English==
===Etymology===
Latin, "let it be done", 3d person singular subjunctive present, from [[fieri]], used as passive of [[facere]] to make. Compare with [[Be]].

===Pronunciation===
IPA: [[WEAE]] /ˈfi.æt/

===Noun===
# An authoritative command or order to do something; an effectual decree.
#:    His fiat laid the corner stone. --Willis.
# (English Law) (a) A warrant of a judge for certain processes. (b) An authority for certain proceedings given by the Lord Chancellor's signature.

====Related Terms====
[[Fiat money]] = irredeemable paper currency, not resting on a specie basis, but deriving its purchasing power from the declaratory fiat of the government issuing it.
